definitions.definition: To get into or inside something, literally or figuratively.
definitions.example: He tried to go after the ball but couldn't get in the game.

definitions.definition: To enter a place; to gain access.
definitions.example: If you want to get in, you'll need the gate code and a key.

definitions.definition: To secure membership at a selective school.
definitions.example: All of our students who applied to university got in.

definitions.definition: To be elected to some office.
definitions.example: Do the early results say our candidate will get in?

definitions.definition: (of evenings or nights) To become dark earlier as a result of seasonal change; to draw in.
definitions.example: Winter's on the way, and the nights are getting in.
It was gone 9 o'clock by the time I got in from work last night.

definitions.definition: An exclamation of joy at one's success.
